<para id="import-auto-id4132060">Notice that this definition indicates that <emphasis effect="italics">velocity is a vector because displacement is a vector</emphasis>. It has both magnitude and direction. The SI unit for velocity is meters per second or m/s, but many other units, such as km/h, mi/h (also written as mph), and cm/s, are in common use. Suppose, for example, an airplane passenger took 5 seconds to move −4 m (the negative sign indicates that displacement is toward the back of the plane). His average velocity would be </para>
